Convert variables to more appropriate Types + make cleaner.¶

In [7]:
# convert X1 into float type, still in percentage
df_1['X1'] = df_1['X1'].str.rstrip("%").astype(float)

# convert X30 into float type, still in percentage
df_1['X30'] = df_1['X30'].str.rstrip("%").astype(float)

# convert X4, X5, X6 into float type from string, still in dollara
df_1['X4'] = df_1['X4'].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
df_1['X5'] = df_1['X5'].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
df_1['X6'] = df_1['X6'].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)

# convert X7 into int type from string
df_1['X7'] = df_1['X7'].str.extract('(\d+)', expand=False)
df_1['X7'] = df_1['X7'].astype(float)

def convert_date(date):
    parts = date.split("-")
    if len(parts[0]) == 2:
        converted = pd.to_datetime(date, format='%d-%b', errors='coerce')
    else:
        converted = pd.to_datetime(date, format='%b-%y', errors='coerce')
    if pd.isna(converted):
        return None
    return converted.strftime('%B-%y')

Brief General Model Evaluation¶

The main 3 models I used and considered were linear regression, Decision Tree Regression, and Gradient Boosting Regression. First, there is linear regression. The model is simple. Being simple means it is easy to understand and easily run on computationally. However, it does not take into account potential outliers or potential correlation between features, which affects predictions. As for, Decision Tree Regression, the output is easily understood and does not need the data to be scaled. However, it takes a long time to run and also can lead to overfitting. Lastly, Gradient Boost Regression, had a lot of flexibility in dealing with both categorical and numerical values (although I did clean my data before). However, it took very long to run and can lead to overfitting.
